# API Contracts & HTTP Conventions

## Contracts live in packages/shared
- Public request/response shapes belong in `packages/shared` (see types rule).
- Don’t expose Prisma model/types as API contracts. Map to API shapes.

## Endpoint design (small-project friendly)
- Use clear resource-oriented routes (nouns), predictable status codes, and consistent naming.
- Keep controllers thin; validation and parsing via DTOs/pipes.

## Error handling
- Use standard Nest `HttpException` subclasses for expected errors.
- Don’t leak internal details in responses (especially in prod). Log details server-side.

## Response shape
- Keep response shapes consistent within a feature.
- Only introduce a global envelope/interceptor when needed and agreed; keep it simple.

## BFF rule (Next as the browser boundary)
- The browser calls `apps/web` route handlers; route handlers proxy to `apps/api`.
- Prefer 1 backend controller/feature ↔ 1 frontend route handler file (see nextjs rule).

## Mutations
- Prefer explicit mutation endpoints (POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE).
- For UX-heavy flows, support “read-after-write” by returning updated resource (or identifiers) and keeping responses deterministic.

